# Implementing Global Colored Category Pills in Elementor (CSS Attribute Method)

This document outlines the steps to style WordPress category tags with distinct colors in an Elementor carousel. This approach uses native Elementor widgets and global Custom CSS, avoiding custom PHP. By targeting the destination URL of each category link via CSS attributes, we can automatically color-code categories like BKO, KYC, and REG across the entire site.

### Prerequisites
* Elementor Pro installed and activated.
* A Loop Item template set up for your posts carousel.
* Post categories properly assigned to your posts (e.g., BKO, KYC, REG).

---

## Step 1: Configure the Post Info Widget
First, we need to output the categories without the default comma separation so they can be styled as individual elements.

1. Open your **Loop Item** template in the Elementor Editor.
2. Drag the **Post Info** widget into your design where you want the tags to appear.
3. Under the **Content** tab, delete the default items (Author, Date, Time, Comments).
4. Add a new item and set its **Type** to **Terms**.
5. Set the **Taxonomy** to **Categories**.
6. Locate the **Separator** field. Delete the default comma (`,`) and replace it with a single space. This breaks the concatenated string into individual link elements.

---

## Step 2: Assign the Custom CSS Class
Next, we give this specific widget a name so our global CSS knows exactly what to target without affecting other lists on your website.

1. With the **Post Info** widget still selected, navigate to the **Advanced** tab.
2. Open the **Layout** panel (usually open by default).
3. In the **CSS Classes** field, type: `custom-category-pills` 
   *(Note: Do not include a dot `.` at the beginning here).*

---

## Step 3: Apply the Global Custom CSS
Now, apply the styling globally. The CSS uses the `href*="value"` attribute selector, which looks at the actual URL of the link to determine which color to apply. 

1. From any Elementor page or template editor, click the **Hamburger Menu** (top left corner) and select **Site Settings**.
2. Scroll down and click on **Custom CSS**.
3. Copy and paste the following CSS code:

```css
/* 1. Flex container to align pills side-by-side */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-items {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
}

/* 2. Base styling for ALL categories (Red) */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-item a {
    padding: 4px 12px;
    border-radius: 12px;
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: #FF545D; 
    background-color: #FF545D1C; 
    transition: opacity 0.3s ease;
}

/* 3. Hover state for all pills */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-item a:hover {
    opacity: 0.8;
}

/* 4. Color override for BKO (Blue Pill) */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-item a[href*="/bko/"] {
    color: #218FAA;
    background-color: #218FAA1A;
}

/* 5. Color override for KYC (Green Pill) */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-item a[href*="/kyc/"] {
    color: #6DA884;
    background-color: #6DA8841A;
}

/* 6. Color override for REG (Orange Pill) */
.custom-category-pills .elementor-icon-list-item a[href*="/reg/"] {
    color: #F78E25;
    background-color: #F78E2521;
}
```

---

## Step 4: Important Adjustments & Troubleshooting

To ensure this works perfectly in your specific environment, verify the following details during implementation:

### 1. Reusing the Design
Anytime you want these colored pills in a new carousel or template, simply add a Post Info widget, set it to Categories, remove the comma separator, and add `custom-category-pills` to the CSS Classes field. You do not need to touch the global CSS again.

### 2. Troubleshooting Permalinks
The CSS provided in Step 3 targets the exact string `/bko/`, `/kyc/`, or `/reg/` inside the category URL. If your colors are not applying, your WordPress permalink structure might be different. 

Hover over one of your category links on the live site and look at the URL. Adjust the `href*=` selector in the CSS accordingly:

* **If your URL is `yoursite.com/category/bko` (no trailing slash):**
  Change `[href*="/bko/"]` to `[href*="/bko"]`
* **If your URL is `yoursite.com/?category_name=bko` (plain permalinks):**
  Change `[href*="/bko/"]` to `[href*="=bko"]`

*Always make sure to match the exact lowercase slug of your category as it appears in the link.*
